{
  "doc_id": "28263",
  "text": "There has been a large and sustained effort to understand both the behaviour of relaxed memory hardware and the concurrent language interface that ought to be presented to programmers. The behaviour of relaxed CPUs is relatively well understood, through formal models of x86 and Power processors that have been validated through testing [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] and communication with architects [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . This line of work has unearthed bugs in deployed CPUs [CITATION_5] , and unexpected behaviours in GPUs that break programming idioms taught in vendor-endorsed documentation [CITATION_6] . Our approach differs from this prior work in that our industrial-academic collaboration is taking place at the research stage, following publicly-released descriptions of the architecture [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] , so the bugs we have found can be rectified before the hardware is deployed.",
